data.content:
`SafeAreaEdges="None"` only tells the page *not* to automatically pad for safe areas — it doesn't force content behind the system bars. You need two more things:

### 1. Mark the view to ignore safe area insets

On the `Image` (or its parent layout), set:

```xml
<Image Source="photo.jpg"
       Aspect="AspectFill"
       IgnoreSafeArea="True"
       VerticalOptions="Fill"
       HorizontalOptions="Fill" />
```

### 2. Go edge-to-edge on Android

Android doesn't render behind system bars by default. In your `MainActivity.cs` (or a page handler), opt in:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    // Render behind status bar and navigation bar
    AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);

    // Make system bars transparent
    Window!.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);
    Window!.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);
}
```

### 3. (iOS) Extend layout under bars

iOS should work with `IgnoreSafeArea="True"` alone, but if not, confirm in a handler:

```csharp
#if IOS
Microsoft.Maui.Handlers.PageHandler.Mapper.AppendToMapping("FullScreen", (handler, view) =>
{
    handler.ViewController!.EdgesForExtendedLayout = UIKit.UIRectEdge.All;
});
#endif
```

**TL;DR:** `SafeAreaEdges="None"` prevents auto-padding but `IgnoreSafeArea="True"` on the view actually extends it behind bars, and Android requires the explicit `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` call.
